Animal based ingredients (other than milk and honey) such as lard, gelatin and meat stock are not used in the traditional cuisine.
The definition of vegetarianism throughout Europe is not uniform, and some local vegetarians are not aware that many products they consume contain ingredients of animal origins, such as rennet, gelatin and more.
In the United Kingdom increasing numbers of the British population have adopted vegetarianism since the end of World War II, especially since the BSE crisis of the 1990s.
